{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かわず}}

{{IPAfont|⟨kapadu⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/kapadu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kafad͡zu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kawad͡zu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kawazu/}}

The more formal or poetic counterpart to ''kaeru'' (see above).<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>  Found in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 CE.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|3|356}}, text [http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man3Yos.html#356 here]</ref>

The ultimate derivation is unclear, but the initial ''kawa'' portion (ancient ''kapa'') is very likely {{m|ja|川}}, {{m|ja|河||tr=kawa, {{upright|ancient}} kapa|river}}.

The phonetic development of the term had already progressed to ''kawadzu'' by 1603, as seen in the ''{{w|Nippo Jisho}}'' entry, spelled ''cauazzu''.<ref>{{R:Nippo Jisho original}}, text [https://books.google.com/books?id=TFJAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PP99#v=onepage&q=cauazzu&f=false here], fifth entry from the bottom of the right-hand column</ref>

{{ja-noun|かわず|hhira=かはづ}}

# {{lb|ja|sort=かわず|poetic}} a [[frog]] {{gloss|amphibious animal}}
# {{lb|ja|sort=かわず|Noh|_|theater}} a specific [[mask]] used in certain [[Noh]] [[play]]s, depicting a [[drowned]] person

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|かいる}}

{{IPAfont|⟨kaperu⟩}}<!-- Cannot find details on the 甲・乙 value of the /e/ vowel --> → {{IPAchar|/kaperu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaferu/}} → {{IPAchar|/kaweru/}} → {{IPAchar|/kajeru/}} → {{IPAchar|/kairu/}}

Sound shift.  Existed alongside earlier ''kayeru'' in the late 1500s, early 1600s, as seen in the 1603 ''{{w|Nippo Jisho}}'' entry, spelled ''cairu''.<ref>{{R:Nippo Jisho original}}, text [https://books.google.com/books?id=TFJAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PP78#v=onepage&q&f=false here] as the fourth entry in the right-hand column, defined in Portuguese as {{m|pt|raã}}, typographic variant of {{m|pt|rãa}}, earlier form of modern {{m|pt|rã||frog}}</ref>

